title: Side Pocket / Tool Holder for Wanhao i3 (Monoprice Maker Select)

description.text:
Side tool pocket for Wanhao i3. It clips onto the right vertical metal Z brace stand, no extra hardware needed. I personally use it to hold a stack of small paper strips for bed leveling.

You can mirror it in Cura or your tool of choice if you want to clip it on the left Z brace stand instead.

Makes sense to print it upside down (clip on the bottom). No support is needed in that case.

A separate test Z clip without the pocket attached is provided. Because of the variances in extrusion width, flow % and so on on different printers, you might want to print the test piece first to make sure it clips tightly on your machine, but without cracking or breaking. Scale the clip and the pocket up or down by some minimal % amount as needed if it's too loose or too tight.

Designed with 1.6 wall thickness which results in Cura generating 2 shells on each side of the wall (total 4) for 0.4 nozzle. No infill needed. Adjust accordingly to your printer/nozzle diameter.

OpenSCAD code provided in case you want to customize this to your needs.

The clip itself is a good starting point for remixing, in case you want to add tool hooks, slotted tool holders and so on instead of the side pocket.

An example of a remix (spatula tool holder) is available here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1529838

title: MK5 / MK6 Thermal Barrier Heatsoak / Cooling Mod

description.text:
[Edit] This failed on me. The holes are too big and the PTFE expanded into the holes under filament pressure. Now I can't extract the filament or the tube. I'm still confident it would still work but with lots of much smaller holes. Next I may just stack TO-5 heatsinks on the tube. A buck each on ePray. [/EDIT] This thing is a modified MK5 / MK6 thermal barrier. The hole arrangement significantly reduces heat conduction / heat soak up the thermal barrier tube.


This arrangement of staggered holes retains structural integrity that is otherwise lost with the horizontal cut-slit method.


This solves or greatly reduces the problem of heat soak during long prints causing filament to soften and / or jam/expand in the PTFE.


The thermal barrier dxf file is Makerbot's not mine.

Use a fine Sharpie and make radial marks on your tube just above the insulation and kapton tape. Make another mark just below the flat barrier plate.


Now make axial marks quartering the tube. Alignment isn't super critical but keeping close will help it look nice and get four holes with a fairly consistent web remaining.


Clamp it horizontally in a vise. Also plan your cuts to cut towards the end, when those four are done, shift out and cut the next four, thus leaving the somewhat weakened piece not bearing any cutting load.


I used a 3/16 end mill to plunge cut each hole. Rotate and cut the remaining 3 on that radius. Shift the thermal barrier tube out of the vise, clamp, index, and repeat.


If you're doing this on a drill press rather than a mill you can use a rat tail file to file a flat spot to help prevent drill bit drifting when starting.


When one use the back of a No 11 Xacto blade or your favorite deburring tool to debur the inside edge of the holes.


Re-assemble your hot end and enjoy minimal heat soak above the thermal core.

title: Messerschmitt Me 262 simplified cnc/laser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Messerschmitt Me-262 was the first plane with jet-engine to be build in series. It was the fastest plane at the time.

My build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 6 mm beech plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. Glued together and nicely sanded it's a great toy for boys (of different age).
A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to create smaller versions.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/Spielsachen/Flugzeugmodelle for more designs.

Keep in mind, that the obj-file is just for validating the construction and viewing in the browser.

I took 3-view drawings of this plane from wikipedia to save the tracing, then used Illustrator to carve out the main features. The slots were a result of trail and error. Before building the plane I did a 3D validation in SketchUp. Then I nested the parts as close as possible for production on a cnc-router.

title: Parkzone P-47 Flap Activated Payload Drop

description.text: I designed and printed this bomb drop for use on my Parkzone P-47. If you attach another servo horn onto the flaps, mount this payload drop under the wing, and cut a push rod to length You should be able to make it work. For the pins I cut off the z bend end of a set of Parkzone P-47 flap push rods and installed servo horns on the outside of the flaps. Where you mount the base will determine the pin length. For mounting I just put two holes in the back side of the base part and threaded some screws through the wings. I have included the SolidWorks files for anyone that wished to modify the parts. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5PLzGexDtTg&feature=share&list=UUQRFnzUWuE9c-lYGHGGb5MQ I finally got the chance to test the system and it works perfectly! http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E98uVY6TAYY&feature=c4-overview&list=UUQRFnzUWuE9c-lYGHGGb5MQ http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cPLomJumsuM&feature=c4-overview&list=UUQRFnzUWuE9c-lYGHGGb5MQ http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VXlno7a_GC4&feature=c4-overview&list=UUQRFnzUWuE9c-lYGHGGb5MQ

comments.author: Heatracer

comments.text: I threw some photos up of how it's attached.  Turns out I added another servo horn straight to the flap itself.  Let me know if you have any more questions
comments.author: Heatracer

comments.text: I'll have to go dig it out, but if i recall, I used a backing plate from a servo horn, and drilled 2 holes down through the wing and drilled and tapped the top of the bomb drop mechanism and ran the two screws into the tapped holes.  Basically mounted it like a servo horn in the middle of the wing.  I then cut and bent a servo push rod that came off of the flap servos up into the bomb mechanism.  That way when the flaps are down, the bombs are held in, and when the flaps are up, Bombs Away!  Hope that helps, I'll see if I can get it dug out tonight and snap some pics.  The pins on the cover didn't really work like i wanted, you could probably just cut them off and drill them out and use screws to mount the cover, I just super glued mine permanent.  Good luck!  Post some pics of your Jug when you get it all done up.

been testing multiple types, models and makes of motors,escs and FC's of late and no matter how good a design of 3d printed hardware is, it'll only stand up to so much testing punishment before your printing replacement parts more than your test flying lol, so I decided to make a small compromise in the build by using a Diatone 250 single piece frame as a base for modification.

FC (frame) platform accommodates anything upto a multiwii or KK2.1 board in size.

Upper platform offers FC protection and maybe somewhere for GPS receiver or VTX.

title: hotshoe mount for celestron red dot star finder

description.text:
This is a quick and dirty hot shoe mount for the red dot finder scope that came with my Celestron telescope. I wanted to be able to use the finder scope with my camera when not attached to a telescope. I'm not sure this will work with any other finder scopes but it seems like there may be some other finder scopes that use the same dovetail design so maybe it will.
Thanks to TheCase for the original Nikon hotshoe cover model. I used it as it was and added the rest of the mount to the top of it. I didn't change the hot shoe part at all and it seems to work fine with my Canon t3i.

Print and use a standard computer case screw for the locking screw. I used an old quick screw from an old computer case so it's easy to tighten with out a screw driver. The hole is a bit small for the screw and could be a little bigger but it worked out well for me and holds nice and tight.

UPDATE: Initially printed this on another printer, but I re-printed this on my MOD-t and it works fine!

To get the housing in place, you'll need to unplug the hot-end and then slide the housing in from the back. I've simply used a big rubber band to hold the housing in place, or you could tape it in place. (Or glue it if you are really confident!) The small vent then slides into place.

If you decide you don't want so much airflow over the nozzle, just pull out vent part and the air will blow out the front instead.

comments.text: I'm scared this will cause filament clogs, as the air is no longer flowing over the whole hot end
comments.author: Zooman009

comments.text: What prevents clogs is having air blowing over the cold end of the filament feed tube, which in the case of the MOD-t, is the entire metal grate on the underside whole extruder head.  With this duct, air still flows over the grate, but it is then redirected in a concentrated flow over the nozzle tip, which is what improves the print quality.

description.text:
I have several bookshelves at home that are about 8ft in the air with neat little storage boxes on them.  Getting them down to dust is kind of a real pain and usually a lot of dust comes down with them.  I thought (in Windows 7 terms) there's got to be a better way!  I designed an attachment for our Dyson vacuum cleaner that fits between the box and sucks up all of the dust, much smarter.
I have included the native Pro/Engineer CAD file for those of you who are lucky enough to have Pro/E, everyone else can use the attached STEP file.

This attachment is really long just over 300mm it was designed to print on my RepStrap which has a build envelope of 325mm x 325mm.  It will definitely not print on the current generation Makerbot.  When printed diagonally on the build base it will require a footprint of about 250mm square.
I have not yet printed it but I am assuming that a heated bed will be necessary to print this without serious warping.
